1. cs.IT (Information Theory): The paper deals with the mutual information of a continuous-time Gaussian channel and its discrete-time counterparts, which is a fundamental concept in information theory. 
2. cs.SI (Signal Processing): The paper discusses the sampling of continuous-time signals, which is a core topic in signal processing. 
3. cs.MM (Multimedia): The paper's focus on sampling and quantifying the mutual information of a continuous-time Gaussian channel has applications in multimedia systems, such as audio and video compression. 
4. cs.NI (Networking and Internet Architecture): The paper's results on how over-sampling approaches the true mutual information of a continuous-time Gaussian channel can have implications for network communication and information transmission. 
5. cs.SP (Speech Processing): The paper's discussion of sampling continuous-time signals and its applications in quantifying mutual information can be relevant to speech processing, which involves analyzing and processing speech signals.
